College Dataset

Kaveh Yousefian

06/30/2021

First Project

Prediction of received applications in College dataset.

“College” dataset contains Statistics for a large number of US Colleges from the 1995 issue of US News and World Report.

More details are available on: https://rdrr.io/cran/ISLR/man/College.html

Goal: Prediction of received application based on other variables and parameters.

Usage :

  • Assessment of Universities performance and ranking,
  • Defining effective parameters on received Application,
  • Proposing strategic plans for improvement of Universities level.

stakeholders:

Universities administrators, managers of Educational institutions, US Departments of education, students

why is beneficial for Stakeholders?

  • Prediction of required facilities.
  • Allocation of sufficient budget and grants,
  • Defining governmental/non-governmental policies,

Variables:

  • X: Name of University,
  • Private: A factor with levels No and Yes indicating private or public university,
  • Apps: Number of applications received,
  • Accept: Number of applications accepted,
  • Enroll: Number of new students enrolled,
  • Top10perc: Pct. new students from top 10% of H.S. class,
  • Top25perc: Pct. new students from top 25% of H.S. class,
  • F.Undergrad: Number of full-time undergraduates,
  • P.Undergrad: Number of part-time undergraduates,
  • Outstate: Out-of-state tuition,
  • Room.Board: Room and board costs,
  • Books: Estimated book costs,
  • Personal: Estimated personal spending,
  • PhD: Pct. of faculty with Ph.D.’s,
  • Terminal: Pct. of faculty with terminal degree,
  • S.F.Ratio: Student/faculty ratio,
  • perc.alumni: Pct. alumni who donate,
  • Expend: Instructional expenditure per student,
  • Grad.Rate: Graduation rate.

Note: Other variables such as annual budget, faculties grant, best Uni subject (engineering, medical, law), citations per faculty, international faculty ratio, international student ratio might help to the better understanding of the purpose.

Note: Removing influential outliers

The model was run several times and it was found that based on cook distance and regression model, observation 484-Rutgers at New Brunswick and 462-Purdue University at West Lafayette is better to remove.There are outliers which have higher impact on regression multipliers.

data_3<-data_3[-which(rownames(data_3) %in% c("Rutgers at New Brunswick", "Purdue University at West Lafayette")),]
set.seed(1234)
train_cases<-sample(1:nrow(data_3),0.7*nrow(data_3))

Unequal variance of Residuals => Heteroscedasticity problem !!

# Predict the results with model 1
pred_lm_1 <- predict(lm_1,test)
abs_err_lm_1 <- abs(pred_lm_1-test$Apps)
MSE_lm_1<-mean((test$Apps-pred_lm_1) ^ 2)
rmse_lm_1 <- sqrt(MSE_lm_1)

MSE_lm_1 = 0.0537785.

RMSE_lm_1 = 0.231902.

Note： Box_cox transformation was applied and the results were checked.

This could not solve the Normality of residuals and the RMSE was obtained higher than the first model. Linear regression model is not a good model for current dataset, however, With the assumption that t-test results are valid, the variable selection was done.

C_1: Linear Regression _ Choosing variables based on t-test

K-fold Cross-Validation Approach in “exhaustive” method

k <- 10
set.seed(1234)
folds <- sample(1:k, nrow(train), rep = TRUE)
cv_errors <- matrix(NA, k, 17, dimnames = list(NULL , paste(1:17)))
#Create prediction function for regsubsets()
#Prediction function
predict_regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id) {
  reg_formula <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat    <- model.matrix(reg_formula, newdata)
  coef_i <- coef(object, id = id)
  mat[, names(coef_i)] %*% coef_i
}

set.seed(123)
for(i in 1:k){
  best_fit <- regsubsets(Apps ~ . , data = train[folds != i,], nvmax = 17, method = "exhaustive")
  for(j in 1:17){
    pred <- predict_regsubsets(best_fit, newdata = train[folds == i,], id = j)
    cv_errors[i, j] <- mean((train$Apps[folds == i] - pred) ^ 2)
  }
}
mean_cv_erros <- apply(cv_errors, 2, mean)

rmse_cv_erros_bestsub <-  sqrt(apply(cv_errors, 2, mean))
plot(rmse_cv_erros_bestsub, pch = 19, type = "b")

The graph shows that RMSE of errors will be minimized with 16 variables with k-fold cross validation method.

#Tuning
#Create hyper-parameter grid
par_grid <- expand.grid(shrinkage = c(0.01, 0.1, 0.3),
                        interaction_depth = c(1, 3, 5), #the maximum depth of each tree
                        n_minobsinnode = c(5, 10, 15),  #the minimum number of observations in the                                      terminal nodes of the trees
                        bag_fraction = c(0.5, 0.7, 0.9) #stochastic gradient:bag.fraction < 1
                        )
nrow(par_grid)
## [1] 81
#Grid search (train/validation approach)
for(i in 1:nrow(par_grid)) {
  set.seed(123)
  #train model
  gbm_tune <- gbm(formula = Apps ~ .,
                  distribution = "gaussian",
                  data = train,
                  n.trees = 5000,
                  interaction.depth = par_grid$interaction_depth[i],
                  shrinkage = par_grid$shrinkage[i],
                  n.minobsinnode = par_grid$n_minobsinnode[i],
                  bag.fraction = par_grid$bag_fraction[i],
                  train.fraction = 0.8,
                  cv.folds = 0,
                  n.cores = NULL, #will use all cores by default
                  verbose = FALSE)  
  #add min training error and trees to grid
  par_grid$optimal_trees[i] <- which.min(gbm_tune$valid.error)
  par_grid$min_RMSE[i]      <- sqrt(min(gbm_tune$valid.error))
}

#Create hyper-parameter grid
par_grid <- expand.grid(eta = c(0.01, 0.05, 0.1, 0.3),
                        lambda = c(0, 50, 100, 1000),
                        max_depth = c(2, 3, 4, 5),
                        subsample = c(0.65, 0.8, 1), 
                        colsample_bytree = c(0.5, 0.8, 0.9, 1))

dim(par_grid)
## [1] 768   5
#Grid search 
for(i in 1:nrow(par_grid )) {
  set.seed(123)
  
  #train model
  xgb_tune <- xgboost(data =  xtrain,
                      label = ytrain,
                      eta = par_grid$eta[i],
                      max_depth = par_grid$max_depth[i],
                      subsample = par_grid$subsample[i],
                      colsample_bytree = par_grid$colsample_bytree[i],
                      nrounds = 1000,
                      objective = "reg:squarederror",  #for regression models
                      verbose = 0,                     #silent,
                      early_stopping_rounds = 10       #stop if no improvement for 10 consecutive trees
  )
  
  #prediction on validation data set
  pred_xgb_validation <- predict(xgb_tune, xvalidation)
  rmse <- sqrt(mean((yvalidation - pred_xgb_validation) ^ 2))
  
  #add validation error
  par_grid$RMSE[i]  <- rmse
}

Model 13: XG Boost Regression
